    bio: `The Church of Kopecky has agreed, after extensive internal deliberation spanning eleven years, to describe Yash as a known deviant and to consider this description complete. Attempts to expand it have been made. The expansions have been read, discussed, and then removed from the official record on the grounds that they contained information the Council was not prepared to canonise without further spiritual preparation, which has not yet been completed.

What is in the record: three of the six books of the Kopeckiad contain sections beginning with the words "On the matter of Yash —" and then immediately change the subject. This was initially attributed to poor editing. It has since been understood as a deliberate choice made by three different scribes working independently, which the Council finds more unsettling than poor editing would have been.

He was present at many of the key events of the Walking. Witnesses describe him consistently as "there, doing something." The something varies in every account. In one account he was "standing near the fire, apparently thinking." In another he was "present and occupied." In a third the witness wrote "Yash was also there" and then crossed it out, then wrote it again, then underscored it. The underscored version is what made it into the final text. The Council asked the scribe about the crossing-out and rewriting. The scribe said: "I decided it was important to include him." When asked why crossing him out had seemed correct first, the scribe said: "That was before I thought about it more."

He was banned from four taverns. The reasons are not given in any official record. Each proprietor declined to state them, though three of the four later invited him back, also without stated reasons. The fourth tavern has maintained the ban. Its proprietor, when asked, says: "I know what I know and some things are between a man and his establishment." This is respected by all parties. Yash himself, when the ban is referenced in his presence, nods in the manner of someone who also knows what the proprietor knows and considers the outcome appropriate.

The goat has its own entry in the Sťažnostná Kniha. It is a footnote of fourteen words. The fourteen words have been the subject of a forty-page analysis by the monastery at Devín. The forty pages do not reach a conclusion. They do note that the goat appears in four separate books of the Kopeckiad and that its presence in scenes is always described in a way that makes it sound like the goat is also doing something, though what the goat is doing is also not recorded. The goat and Yash are, as far as the documentary record can determine, aligned in purpose. This is all the record says. This is enough.`,
