// ─── CHUD QUOTES ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export const CHUD_QUOTES = [
  { text: 'The Chud does not chase. The Chud is simply... present. In the right places. At the right times. Several times. Until circumstances, and occasionally the layout of the village itself, rearrange to agree with him.', source: 'Kopecky, on the Second Pillar · Year Four' },
  { text: 'To be a Chud is to know you are correct and to wait patiently for others to arrive at the same conclusion. The wait can be long. I have waited, on one occasion, longer than the event I was waiting for took to occur, which should not be possible, and I did not find it remarkable, which the scribes found the most remarkable part.', source: 'Kopecky, to the assembly at Zlaté Moravce · Year Six' },
  { text: 'I am not lonely. I am solitary. One is chosen and one is a condition; I have made the choice and therefore I am fine. I would explain further but I have somewhere I need to be. I do not currently have somewhere I need to be. I will have had somewhere I needed to be, retroactively, once I arrive. This is also fine.', source: 'Kopecky, when asked directly · Nitra, Year Five' },
  { text: 'A woman who does not appreciate the Chud has not yet encountered a Chud under optimal conditions. The Chud is aware of this. The Chud finds it clarifying. The Chud has calculated the optimal conditions to four decimal places and is, the Chud will note, fine.', source: 'Kopecky, at the evening assembly · Prvá Dolina, Year Seven' },
  { text: 'The Chud reads. The Chud knows things. The Chud tells people the things he knows, because they deserve to know them. If people do not wish to be told, the Chud tells them more slowly, in case the issue was speed. If the issue was not speed, the Chud has, on at least one occasion, told them in a dream, which they confirmed the next morning, unsettled.', source: 'Kopecky, on the Eighth Law · Year Six' },
  { text: 'I have walked from the Tatras to the Danube and back. The mountains are the same. The river is the same. The people are the same. The bread is getting worse, and it is getting worse faster than people are getting worse, which means something is happening to the bread specifically, and I intend to find out what.', source: 'Kopecky, returning from the southern valleys · Tatranská Kniha, Chapter 8' },
  { text: 'If you must ask whether the fire is ready, it is not ready. If you must ask whether the man is trustworthy, he is not. Uncertainty about a question is usually the answer. I have never been uncertain. This is not arrogance; it is simply that the answers tend to arrive before the questions, and I have learned to read them in that order.', source: 'Kopecky, to the council of elders at Nitra · Year Seven' },
  { text: 'The mountains were there before me. But I was there before the mountains knew what they were for. They have thanked me, in the way mountains thank — slowly, geologically, in a manner most people mistake for erosion.', source: 'Kopecky, upon arriving at Prvá Dolina · Tatranská Kniha, Chapter 1' },
  { text: 'There is a dish I will not make. There is an object I will not open. I am, in the end, mostly a list of things I have correctly declined to do. This is not a small thing to be. Most men are a list of things they did anyway.', source: 'Kopecky, unprompted, during a discussion about fence posts · Year Ten' },
  { text: 'Saad weeps over a tangerine and means it more than you have meant anything in your life. I do not understand it. I have stopped trying to. There are three things I no longer try to understand: the fog, the dish, and Saad. I am at peace with all three. I am most at peace with the fog.', source: 'Kopecky, to Vladimír · Year Eleven' },
  { text: 'Nekro does not speak because she has concluded your words are inadequate to what she is. I have reviewed the available words. She is not entirely wrong. We are both creatures of some kind. We recognise each other across the gap. I will not be explaining the gap.', source: 'Kopecky, to the Council of Devín · Year Twelve' },
]

