    title:'The Night of the Forbidden Mac and Cheese',
    body:`What is known is incomplete, because every account is incomplete, and each is incomplete in a different place, as though the night itself resists being assembled — three scribes who pooled their accounts reported the pooled account was <em>more</em> incomplete than any single one, and one of them forgot how to write the word "cheese" for a year. Kopecky prepared a dish. Pasta. Cheese. A third thing. The third thing is recorded only as a temperature and a sound. Those present agree he was unusually quiet, that he stopped partway, looked at what he had done, and put it away without serving it, and that for the duration of the cooking no one in the room could remember the name of their own father. When Vladimír asked, gently, whether it was a metaphor, Kopecky looked at him a long time and said: "You would prefer that it were." The dish has never been made again. He guards it not with silence, as he guards the satchel, but by speaking of it constantly while revealing nothing — a method he considers superior, and which the Council, after long study, has been forced to agree is superior, which troubles them more than the dish. Saad wept. He has declined to say why, which for Saad is itself unusual.`
